SIMPLE: roll
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Roll
<hw>Roll</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Rolled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rolling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>roeler</ets>,
<ets>roler</ets>, F. <ets>rouler</ets>, LL. <ets>rotulare</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>royulus</ets>, <ets>rotula</ets>, a little wheel, dim. of
<ets>rota</ets> wheel; akin to G. <ets>rad</ets>, and to Skr.
<ets>ratha</ets> car, chariot. Cf. <er>Control</er>, <er>Roll</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <er>Rotary</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to
revolve by turning over and over; to move by turning on an axis; to
impel forward by causing to turn over and over on a supporting surface;
<as>as, to <ex>roll</ex> a wheel, a ball, or a barrel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wrap round on itself; to form into a spherical or
cylindrical body by causing to turn over and over; <as>as, to
<ex>roll</ex> a sheet of paper; to <ex>roll</ex> parchment; to
<ex>roll</ex> clay or putty into a ball.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bind or involve by winding, as in a bandage; to
inwrap; -- often with <xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>roll</ex> up a
parcel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To drive or impel forward with an easy motion, as of
rolling; <as>as, a river <ex>rolls</ex> its waters to the
ocean</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The flood of Catholic reaction was <qex>rolled</qex> over
Europe.</q> <rj><qau>J. A. Symonds.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To utter copiously, esp. with sounding words; to
utter with a deep sound; -- often with <xex>forth</xex>, or
<xex>out</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>roll</ex> forth some one's praises; to
<ex>roll</ex> out sentences.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who <qex>roll'd</qex> the psalm to wintry skies.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To press or level with a roller; to spread or form
with a roll, roller, or rollers; <as>as, to <ex>roll</ex> a field; to
<ex>roll</ex> paste; to <ex>roll</ex> steel rails, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To move, or cause to be moved, upon, or by means of,
rollers or small wheels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To beat with rapid, continuous strokes, as a drum;
to sound a roll upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>To apply (one line or surface) to
another without slipping; to bring all the parts of (one line or
surface) into successive contact with another, in suck manner that at
every instant the parts that have been in contact are equal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To turn over in one's mind; to revolve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full oft in heart he <qex>rolleth</qex> up and down⟦br⟧
The beauty of these florins new and bright.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 11. To rob, usu. a person unable to resist, as an unconscious,
drunk, or sleeping person, by removing valuables on his person; as, to
roll a drunk. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To roll one's self</b></col>, <cd>to wallow.</cd> --
<col><b>To roll the eye</b></col>, <cd>to direct its axis hither and
thither in quick succession.</cd> -- <col><b>To roll one's
r's</b></col>, <cd>to utter the letter <xex>r</xex> with a trill.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Roll
<hw>Roll</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move, as a curved
object may, along a surface by rotation without sliding; to revolve upon
an axis; to turn over and over; <as>as, a ball or wheel <ex>rolls</ex>
on the earth; a body <ex>rolls</ex> on an inclined plane.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And her foot, look you, is fixed upon a spherical stone, which
<qex>rolls</qex>, and <qex>rolls</qex>, and <qex>rolls</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move on wheels; <as>as, the carriage
<ex>rolls</ex> along the street</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>rolling</xex> chair.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be wound or formed into a cylinder or ball;
<as>as, the cloth <ex>rolls</ex> unevenly; the snow <ex>rolls</ex>
well.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To fall or tumble; -- with <xex>over</xex>; <as>as,
a stream <ex>rolls</ex> over a precipice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To perform a periodical revolution; to move onward
as with a revolution; <as>as, the <ex>rolling</ex> year; ages
<ex>roll</ex> away.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To turn; to move circularly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And his red eyeballs <qex>roll</qex> with living fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To move, as waves or billows, with alternate swell
and depression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What different sorrows did within thee <qex>roll</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To incline first to one side, then to the other; to
rock; <as>as, there is a great difference in ships about
<ex>rolling</ex></as>; in a general semse, to be tossed about.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Twice ten tempestuous nights I <qex>rolled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To turn over, or from side to side, while lying
down; to wallow; <as>as, a horse <ex>rolls</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To spread under a roller or rolling-pin; <as>as,
the paste <ex>rolls</ex> well</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To beat a drum with strokes so rapid that they can
scarcely be distinguished by the ear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>To make a loud or heavy rumbling noise; <as>as, the
thunder <ex>rolls</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To roll about</b></col>, <cd>to gad abroad.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Man shall not suffer his wife go <qex>roll about</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Roll
<hw>Roll</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>r⟦ocir⟧le</ets> a roll (in
sense 3), fr. L. <ets>rotulus <?/</ets> little wheel, LL., a roll, dim.
of L. <ets>rota</ets> a wheel. See <er>Roll</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, and cf.
<er>R⟦ocir⟧le</er>, <er>Rouleau</er>, <er>Roulette</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of rolling, or state of being rolled; <as>as,
the <ex>roll</ex> of a ball; the <ex>roll</ex> of waves</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which rolls; a roller.</def> Specifically:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>A heavy cylinder used to break clods.</def>
<au>Mortimer.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of a set of revolving
cylinders, or rollers, between which metal is pressed, formed, or
smoothed, as in a rolling mill; <as>as, to pass rails through the
<ex>rolls</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is rolled up; <as>as, a <ex>roll</ex> of
fat, of wool, paper, cloth, etc.</as></def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>A document written on a piece of parchment, paper, or other
materials which may be rolled up; a scroll.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Busy angels spread⟦br⟧
The lasting <qex>roll</qex>, recording what we say.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1249 --></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Hence, an official or public document; a register;
a record; also, a catalogue; a list.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>rolls</qex> of Parliament, the entry of the petitions,
answers, and transactions in Parliament, are extant.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M.
Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>roll</qex> and list of that army doth remain.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>A quantity of cloth wound into a cylindrical form;
<as>as, a <ex>roll</ex> of carpeting; a <ex>roll</ex> of
ribbon</as>.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>A cylindrical twist of
tobacco.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A kind of shortened raised biscuit or bread, often
rolled or doubled upon itself.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The oscillating movement of a
vessel from side to side, in sea way, as distinguished from the
alternate rise and fall of bow and stern called
<xex>pitching</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A heavy, reverberatory sound; <as>as, the <ex>roll
of</ex> cannon, or of thunder</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The uniform beating of a drum with strokes so rapid
as scarcely to be distinguished by the ear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Part; office; duty; role.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Long roll</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a prolonged
roll of the drums, as the signal of an attack by the enemy, and for the
troops to arrange themselves in line.</cd> -- <col><b>Master of the
rolls</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Master</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Roll
call</b></col>, <cd>the act, or the time, of calling over a list names,
as among soldiers.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Rolls of court</b></col>,
<col><b>of parliament</b></col></mcol> (or of any public body), <cd>the
parchments or rolls on which the acts and proceedings of that body are
engrossed by the proper officer, and which constitute the records of
such public body.</cd> -- <col><b>To call the roll</b></col>, <cd>to
call off or recite a list or roll of names of persons belonging to an
organization, in order to ascertain who are present or to obtain
responses from those present.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- List; schedule; catalogue; register; inventory.
See <er>List</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rollable</ent>⟦br⟧
